00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:28.600
was that their caregiver
suddenly passed away.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:31.700
Every time someone left the house,

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:33.540
they were being put in restraints,

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:35.830
or they were being moved
to a different facility.

00:15:35.830 --> 00:15:38.360
Every time strangers came to the home,

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:41.280
that meant that something
bad was going to happen.

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:43.812
Every time they interacted with people,

00:15:43.812 --> 00:15:47.290
the reciprocal interaction was negative.

00:15:47.290 --> 00:15:49.460
And so those things were forgotten,

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:51.060
but all they wanted to happen

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:54.560
was for us to fix Johnny
leaving the house,

00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:56.490
Susan coming out of her room,

00:15:56.490 --> 00:15:58.810
or someone else eating green things.

00:15:58.810 --> 00:16:02.210
And so often times, our
job was to bring back

00:16:02.210 --> 00:16:05.130
into perspective the
entire experience that

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:06.610
that person brought with them,

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:09.510
so that we can build the
empathy and compassion

00:16:09.510 --> 00:16:12.470
in the care again, so that
in the day-to-day caregiving,

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:14.060
we didn't forget those things.

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:17.150
So instead of put your hands down,

00:16:17.150 --> 00:16:19.480
stop blocking us from leaving the door,

00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:23.460
it's gonna be okay, we're not
gonna take you somewhere else,

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:26.810
you live here forever, we're
just going to your day program.

00:16:26.810 --> 00:16:29.920
Because sometimes those
little changes in tone,

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:33.270
attitude, and approach
made a huge difference

00:16:33.270 --> 00:16:34.830
in the day-to-day functioning

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:37.130
of the individual that
we were there to serve.

00:16:40.750 --> 00:16:43.610
- [Dr. Kripke] And the
richness of these comprehensive

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:46.460
consults were really to dig
deep into their past history,

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:50.060
not just what the people in
their present lives know,

00:16:50.060 --> 00:16:54.560
but to dig as deeply
as we could to find out

00:16:54.560 --> 00:16:56.270
what people's stories were,

00:16:56.270 --> 00:16:58.340
and once you understood that context,

00:16:58.340 --> 00:17:03.250
it really made a huge
difference in their care.

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:07.720
We focused, the team experimented

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:11.260
with a variety of ways
to create efficiencies,

00:17:11.260 --> 00:17:14.010
with the hope that we
could reduce the amount

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:15.840
of highly skilled labor, travel,

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:19.580
or resources that we needed
to do solid assessments,

00:17:19.580 --> 00:17:21.390
and to create comprehensive

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:24.610
and practical sets of recommendations.

00:17:24.610 --> 00:17:28.460
But what we found was that there's really,

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:31.350
there are no shortcuts, that
this is labor-intensive,

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:35.600
that it takes expertise,
that it takes the whole team,

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:37.680
and that it takes going
to their environment,

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:39.340
we can't do this by telemedicine.

00:17:39.340 --> 00:17:41.490
And we actually serve some people

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:45.010
that the TACT team had served,
and who provided services to,

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:46.590
but when we went out there,

00:17:46.590 --> 00:17:48.010
we had a really different perspective,

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:49.740
and a different set of recommendations

00:17:49.740 --> 00:17:53.150
than when it was done completely remotely.

00:17:53.150 --> 00:17:57.470
So taking the time also, to
write our comprehensive reports

00:17:57.470 --> 00:18:00.790
was very labor-intensive,
but synthesizing that data

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:04.060
from multiple disciplines
and multiple sources

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:08.300
was a critical services to
get teams on the same page,

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:11.300
and to create a common understanding
of what the issues were

00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:14.680
so that people could work
together effectively.

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:18.120
We often thought that we
had a really good idea

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:19.700
of what was going on with the client

00:18:19.700 --> 00:18:21.940
based on talking to
their case coordinators,

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:24.840
and doing that comprehensive
review of records,

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:29.030
which was often a quite thick stack.

00:18:29.030 --> 00:18:33.830
But even the reason for
the consult was different

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.960
when we actually got out there,

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:39.520
even the chief complaint wasn't the same.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.690
And if we don't understand
the nature of the problem,

00:18:42.690 --> 00:18:47.360
like you were alluding to Zoe,
then we can end up spending

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:50.840
an awful lot of resources,
getting very frustrated,

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:55.150
and not providing an
effective service for that,

00:18:55.150 --> 00:18:57.760
so doing that deep dive,

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:00.190
and finding out what the real issue was,

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:02.650
often the solutions
weren't that complicated.

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:06.780
Sometimes they were, they
usually were not more expensive

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:10.340
than what was already being
spent on these clients

00:19:10.340 --> 00:19:13.290
who were the people who were in

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:15.700
the most difficult situations,

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:17.100
and so we were already spending

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:18.460
an enormous amount of resources,

00:19:18.460 --> 00:19:21.280
a lot of people were
involved in their care,

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:24.853
but ineffective services
aren't cost-effective ever.

00:19:27.107 --> 00:19:28.710
For example, we were told that somebody

00:19:28.710 --> 00:19:31.370
was very highly aggressive,
but what we found was

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:32.950
that they had a neurological tick,

00:19:32.950 --> 00:19:36.223
and if you happen to get in the
way, it wasn't a good thing.

00:19:37.944 --> 00:19:40.290
And or, we were told that they were sick

00:19:40.290 --> 00:19:41.260
and failing to thrive,

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:43.430
and they were getting very
expensive medical workups,

00:19:43.430 --> 00:19:44.450
and when we got out there,

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:46.973
we found that there was
no food in their cupboard.

00:19:48.620 --> 00:19:52.860
It takes experience, and
expertise to sort out

00:19:52.860 --> 00:19:56.900
clients who have complex
combinations of developmental,

00:19:56.900 --> 00:19:58.840
medical, behavioral, psychiatric,

00:19:58.840 --> 00:20:02.480
and environmental issues,
and to tell a coherent story

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:07.310
about where they've been
and to tell a coherent story

00:20:07.310 --> 00:20:08.500
about what needs to be done

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:10.430
to get them where they need to be,

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:13.273
and there really isn't
a shortcut for that.

00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:19.480
And so we were only, in
order to expand the impact

00:20:19.750 --> 00:20:23.810
of our work beyond the
individuals that we worked with,

00:20:23.810 --> 00:20:27.970
we did a lot of follow-up
work that impacted

00:20:27.970 --> 00:20:30.610
the entire community, and
helped to build the workforce,

00:20:30.610 --> 00:20:31.670
which was really the goal.

00:20:31.670 --> 00:20:34.670
For example, a recurring theme

00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:38.840
was that attitudes were a major barrier

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:43.220
to healthcare access, and we
went to the local hospitals,

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:45.870
and we talked to the
local service providers,

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:49.440
and we empowered the
local service providers

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:54.070
to provide information, and
we met with Grand Rounds,

00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:57.380
we met with the local
providers to really explain

00:20:57.380 --> 00:20:59.740
who people with developmental
disabilities are,

00:20:59.740 --> 00:21:04.740
what their potential is, and
why they should receive care

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:07.250
and services like anybody else.

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:11.340
We did quite a bit of training,

00:21:11.340 --> 00:21:14.090
especially around communication,

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:16.580
around goals of care conversations,

00:21:16.580 --> 00:21:19.010
and on successful community living,

00:21:19.010 --> 00:21:21.240
and that really changed the relationship

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:23.960
between these healthcare facilities,

00:21:23.960 --> 00:21:25.410
and healthcare provider groups,

00:21:25.410 --> 00:21:28.580
and the regional centers,
and their clients.

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:32.640
We also invited local community clinicians

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:35.290
to come to our comprehensive consults,

00:21:35.290 --> 00:21:38.420
and watch us work with the
patients that they were serving,

00:21:38.420 --> 00:21:40.450
and that they had been struggling through,

00:21:40.450 --> 00:21:43.240
trying to diagnose, and trying to serve,

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:45.190
and went to them,

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:50.190
and talked to them about
their challenging situations.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:52.880
Medical education doesn't, I mean,

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.644
this is a fabulous conference,

00:21:54.644 --> 00:21:57.660
and medical articles are great,

00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:59.990
but medical education
is apprenticeship style,

00:21:59.990 --> 00:22:03.550
we have to show people how to do,

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:04.890
we can't just talk about it,

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:07.680
we have to show it in
practice with their patients,

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:10.290
in the context that
they're actually practicing

00:22:10.290 --> 00:22:11.690
for people to get better at it.

00:22:11.690 --> 00:22:14.060
And by going out to these communities,

00:22:14.060 --> 00:22:16.190
and doing these consults,
we were able to do that

00:22:16.190 --> 00:22:19.450
kind of very hands-on training,

00:22:19.450 --> 00:22:24.373
and to model what we teach in practice.

00:22:25.716 --> 00:22:30.140
And in terms of systems issues, there is,

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:34.890
a lot of focus is on the
services that are being provided

00:22:34.890 --> 00:22:37.750
in higher level group homes,
and medically oriented,

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:40.141
and behaviorally oriented group homes,

00:22:40.141 --> 00:22:44.930
but most of our clients
were not in those homes,

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:48.180
and most people with
developmental disabilities

00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:49.700
don't live in those homes.

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:54.070
So if you focus solely on the people

00:22:54.070 --> 00:22:55.460
who are living in those homes,

00:22:55.460 --> 00:22:58.200
we're really gonna miss the boat on

00:23:00.070 --> 00:23:02.530
improving healthcare for the population,

00:23:02.530 --> 00:23:05.313
which includes 300,000 people,

00:23:06.350 --> 00:23:08.220
only a handful of which live

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:10.760
in these higher level group homes.

00:23:10.760 --> 00:23:13.910
Family, direct support professionals,

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:18.200
service providers, they're
front-line healthcare workers.

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:22.280
They recognize illness,
they provide the support

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:24.450
when people are accessing medical care,

00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:26.800
they implement the healthcare plans,

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:30.360
and those people need training,
support, and oversight.

00:23:30.360 --> 00:23:32.290
And when we went into these communities,

00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:34.660
we were able to provide them
with some of that training,

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:36.600
and support, and encouragement,

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:40.840
and recognition for the
important role that they have,

00:23:40.840 --> 00:23:42.920
and the important job that they're doing

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:44.700
that impacts healthcare,

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:46.780
it's not just about what doctors do,

00:23:46.780 --> 00:23:49.100
it's not just what clinicians do,

00:23:49.100 --> 00:23:50.720
it's not just what nurses do,

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:55.370
it's also those hands-on support people,

00:23:55.370 --> 00:23:58.550
and families that are
making a big difference.

00:23:58.550 --> 00:24:02.750
And we also notice that, in
terms of system problems,

00:24:02.750 --> 00:24:07.410
that we focus so much on these high-level

00:24:07.410 --> 00:24:10.770
group homes that have a lot
of medical resources in them,

00:24:10.770 --> 00:24:15.259
and while they're fabulous,
and necessary, and important,

00:24:15.259 --> 00:24:18.990
a recurrent theme was
that people who don't live

00:24:18.990 --> 00:24:21.230
in those homes, don't have
access to skilled nursing,

00:24:21.230 --> 00:24:23.400
even when they have skilled nursing needs,

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:26.850
and a lot of people are being
forced into institutions,

00:24:26.850 --> 00:24:30.780
into SNFs, into out-of-state placements

00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:34.610
because they don't have
access to skilled nursing

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:36.180
when they live in supported living,

00:24:36.180 --> 00:24:38.220
when they live in family homes,

00:24:38.220 --> 00:24:42.500
when they live in
behaviorally oriented homes.

00:24:42.500 --> 00:24:45.270
Another theme was access
to mental health services

00:24:45.270 --> 00:24:48.640
that have expertise in
developmental disabilities.

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:52.080
There are some fields where
taking care of a person

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:53.500
with a developmental disability,

00:24:53.500 --> 00:24:56.179
isn't that different than
taking care of everybody else,

00:24:56.179 --> 00:25:01.160
but primary care, and
mental and behavioral health

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:04.120
are definitely areas where

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:06.450
special expertise is needed,

00:25:06.450 --> 00:25:11.330
and there is a lack of
access to mental healthcare

00:25:11.330 --> 00:25:14.190
in general, but a tremendous,

00:25:14.190 --> 00:25:18.410
tremendous lack of people
who have actual expertise,

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:22.090
and we're just so glad to have

00:25:22.090 --> 00:25:26.780
Dr. Ihle on the team, and doing training,

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:29.890
and providing us with that support,

00:25:29.890 --> 00:25:33.310
because non of the other team
members were able to make

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:34.720
the kinds of recommendations,

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:39.180
and to make the kinds of
insights that she was able to do,

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:42.930
that's tremendously important,
and we need to reproduce her.

00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:47.930
And a final thing is around
inter-agency collaboration.

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:51.110
There's an awful lot of different people,

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:52.570
whether it's regional centers,

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:57.570
local medical centers, and hospitals,

00:25:58.140 --> 00:26:01.833
local, the county mental health systems,

00:26:03.010 --> 00:26:06.910
and more, and the direct
service providers,

00:26:06.910 --> 00:26:10.823
the families, the schools, every,

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:14.790
all of those different systems,

00:26:14.790 --> 00:26:17.800
and local service providers too,

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:21.510
the local agencies who
are providing services,

00:26:21.510 --> 00:26:23.090
the parent information training centers,

00:26:23.090 --> 00:26:26.580
all of these people have a
role in promoting health,

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:30.460
and we need to work together,

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:32.140
and we need to break down the barriers

00:26:32.140 --> 00:26:34.630
that we're not just
pointing fingers and saying,

00:26:34.630 --> 00:26:35.750
oh, that's your health plan,

00:26:35.750 --> 00:26:37.090
oh, that's the regional center,

00:26:37.090 --> 00:26:38.860
oh, that's county mental health,

00:26:38.860 --> 00:26:41.970
and so that we can not replicate services,

00:26:41.970 --> 00:26:44.320
because a lot of times
each of those agencies

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:46.270
has a different care coordinator,

00:26:46.270 --> 00:26:48.910
and we're doing a lot of duplicate work

00:26:48.910 --> 00:26:50.248
that we could be doing once.

00:26:50.248 --> 00:26:53.020
And then we need to break down,

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:55.840
make real decisions
about who's responsible

00:26:55.840 --> 00:26:59.520
for what when we have these
complicated situations,

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:02.670
so that we can work as a team,

00:27:02.670 --> 00:27:06.393
not just this team, but
also that community team.

00:27:07.270 --> 00:27:08.103
Thanks.

00:27:09.202 --> 00:27:11.119
- You have two minutes.

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.260
- [Dr. Ihle] I feel that
we're so far behind,

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:22.277
but I'll just put in a plug
for psychiatry (laughs).

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:28.870
As the discipline that focuses on

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:33.380
trying to understand whether there are

00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:36.970
neurophysiological underpinnings

00:27:36.970 --> 00:27:38.460
to changes in behavior,

00:27:38.460 --> 00:27:41.140
and the changes in behavior
that we are often asked

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:43.490
to consult on were either

00:27:44.330 --> 00:27:46.620
decreases in functionality,

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:51.580
or worsening behavior
in terms of agitation,

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:54.240
or what was called disruptive behavior.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:56.300
And if we think about these things

00:27:56.300 --> 00:28:00.600
as manifestations of what the physiology

00:28:00.600 --> 00:28:02.423
of the nervous system is doing,

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:06.810
then I think that will also
provide additional insights

00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:10.590
that maybe the care providers
hadn't been considering,

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:14.303
or hadn't been included in the care plans.

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:19.430
- Final words?

00:28:19.430 --> 00:28:23.040
I just want to give a shout-out
to our caregiving team here,

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:26.870
care provider support
assessment, Pat and Joe,

00:28:26.870 --> 00:28:28.930
did a great job, and I
think that is something

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:32.990
that often times, not included,

00:28:32.990 --> 00:28:35.360
and actually is a really important part

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:36.980
in terms of someone's health.

00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:39.850
We know the caregiving forces is aging,

00:28:39.850 --> 00:28:43.230
and we know that we need
more good caregivers,

00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:45.420
and they need support

00:28:45.420 --> 00:28:47.570
to do the kind of job
that they have to do.

